Supervised Learning Project

Data Description: The file Bank.xls contains data on 5000 customers. The data include customer demographic information (age, income, etc.), the customer's relationship with the bank (mortgage, securities account, etc.), and the customer response to the last personal loan campaign (Personal Loan). Among these 5000 customers, only 480 (= 9.6%) accepted the personal loan that was offered to them in the earlier campaign.

Domain:Banking

Context:This case is about a bank (Thera Bank) whose management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors). A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio with minimal budget.

Attribute Information:

  1. ID: Customer ID
  2. Age: Customer's age in completed years
  3. Experience: #years of professional experience
  4. Income: Annual income of the customer (in thousands of dollars)
  5. ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code.
  6. Family: Family size of the customer
  7. CCAvg: Avg. spending on credit cards per month (in thousands of dollars)
  8. Education: Education Level.
    1. Undergrad
    2. Graduate
    3. Advanced/Professional
  9. Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any. (in thousands of dollars)
  10. Personal Loan : Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign?
  11. Securities Account : Does the customer have a securities account with the bank?
  12. CD Account : Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank?
  13. Online : Does the customer use internet banking facilities?
  14. Credit card : Does the customer use a credit card issued by UniversalBank?

The classification goal is to predict the likelihood of a liability customer buying personal loans.

# preparing data
# eliminating columns of ID, ZIP Code and Experience as they dont influence the predictor variable

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

X = loan.drop(columns = ['ID', 'ZIP Code', 'Experience', 'Personal Loan'])     # Predictor feature columns
Y = loan['Personal Loan']   # Predicted class (1=True, 0=False)

In [21]:
# Logistic Regression
from sklearn import metrics

from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

# Fit the model on train
lr = LogisticRegression(C=1e5)
lr.fit(x_train, y_train)

from sklearn import metrics

lr_train_predict = lr.predict(x_train)
lr_test_predict = lr.predict(x_test)


print("Model Accuracy for Training Data: {0:.4f}".format(metrics.accuracy_score(y_train, lr_train_predict)))
print("Model Accuracy for Testing Data: {0:.4f}".format(metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, lr_test_predict)))

cm=metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, lr_test_predict, labels=[1, 0])
print('\nConfusion Matrix:\n', cm)

# Classification Report
print('\n{}'.format(classification_report(y_test, lr_test_predict)))

# Accuracy Score
auc = accuracy_score(y_test, lr_test_predict)
print('\nAccuracy Score:\n', auc.round(3))

#KNN

from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from scipy.stats import zscore

NNH = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors= 5 , weights = 'distance' )
NNH.fit(x_train, y_train)

# For every test data point, predict it's label based on 5 nearest neighbours in this model.

NNH_train_predict = NNH.predict(x_train)
NNH_test_predict = NNH.predict(x_test)


print('k-Nearest Neighbor Classifier Scores after Scaling without Hyperparameter Tuning\n\n')
print('k-NN accuracy for train set: {0:.3f}'.format(NNH.score(x_train, y_train)))
print('k-NN accuracy for test set: {0:.3f}'.format(NNH.score(x_test, y_test)))

# Classification Report
print('\n{}'.format(classification_report(y_test, NNH_test_predict)))

# Confusion Matrix
cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, NNH_test_predict)
print('\nConfusion Matrix:\n', cm)

# Accuracy Score
auc = accuracy_score(y_test, NNH_test_predict)
print('\nAccuracy Score:\n', auc.round(3))

# Logistic Regression
from sklearn import metrics

from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

# Fit the model on train
lr_scale = LogisticRegression(C=1e5)
lr_scale.fit(x_train, y_train)

from sklearn import metrics

lr_scale_train_predict = lr_scale.predict(x_train)
lr_scale_test_predict = lr_scale.predict(x_test)

print("Model Accuracy for Training Data: {0:.4f}".format(metrics.accuracy_score(y_train, lr_scale_train_predict)))
print("Model Accuracy for Testing Data: {0:.4f}".format(metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, lr_scale_test_predict)))

cm=metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, lr_scale_test_predict, labels=[1, 0])
print('\nConfusion Matrix:\n', cm)

# Classification Report
print('\n{}'.format(classification_report(y_test, lr_scale_test_predict)))

# Accuracy Score
auc = accuracy_score(y_test, lr_scale_test_predict)
print('\nAccuracy Score:\n', auc.round(3))

Output¶

  1. Type 1 models - without scaling

    1. Logistic Regression | Comparing Accuracy and F1 score: 0.95 and 0.97
    2. Naive Bayes | Comparing Accuracy and F1 score: 0.893 and 0.94
    3. KNN | Comparing Accuracy and F1 score: 0.924 and 0.96

  2. Type 2 models - with scaling

    1. Logistic Regression - Comparing Accuracy and F1 score: 0.95 and 0.97
    2. Naive Bayes - Comparing Accuracy and F1 score: 0.893 and 0.94
    3. KNN - Comparing Accuracy and F1 score: 0.963 and 0.98

  3. Type 3 models - without scaling and crossvalidation

    1. Logistic Regression | Crossvalidation Score: 0.947
    2. Naive Bayes | Crossvalidation Score: 0.884
    3. KNN | Crossvalidation Score: 0.915

  4. Type 4 models - with scaling and crossvalidation

    1. Logistic Regression | Crossvalidation Score: 0.950
    2. Naive Bayes | Crossvalidation Score: 0.883
    3. KNN | Crossvalidation Score: 0.961

Observations¶

  1. Logistic Reggression and Naive Bayes models have performed closely on the test and train data test and it can be called a fair fit without any cases of overfitting or underfitting except for KNN which had a perfect fit accuracy on train data and was marginally overfitting on the test data
  2. For a raw model without scaling and crossvalidation, Logistic Regression performs well followed by KNN and Naive Bayes
  3. For a scaled model without crossvalidation, KNN performs better followed by Logistic Regression and Naive Bayes
  4. For a raw model with crossvalidation, Logistic Regression performs the best follwed by KNN and Naive Bayes
  5. For a scaled model with crossvalidation, KNN performs the best followed by Logistic Regression and Naive Bayes

In this scenario it will be beneficial to work with Logistic Regression as it performs better across all configurations.
